    <section>
      <h2>The Lewiston-Auburn Cannabis Landscape</h2>
      <p>Five to seven licensed dispensaries currently operate in the Lewiston-Auburn area. This density is approaching saturation by Maine standards, particularly given that the L-A metro has roughly 60,000 potential customers versus Portland's 70,000 with only 10-12 dispensaries. The per-capita dispensary ratio in Lewiston-Auburn is notably higher than other Maine markets of comparable size.</p>
      <p>The existing dispensaries are not uniformly distributed. They cluster along the Lisbon Street corridor and in the downtown Center Street area. This clustering means certain neighborhoods—the Tree Streets district, the Hillcrest area, and the Lewiston-Auburn College campus surroundings—lack nearby dispensary access. A location in one of these underserved neighborhoods might capture customers who currently have to drive to Lisbon Street or downtown.</p>
      <p>Customer loyalty is where the real competition lives. Each established dispensary has accumulated regulars over years of operation. These customers have relationships with budtenders, know the product selection, and have established buying patterns. Convincing them to switch requires a compelling reason—not just proximity or price, but a genuine differentiation in experience, product, or philosophy.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The Saturation Challenge</h2>
      <p>Lewiston already has 5-7 dispensaries. The market is approaching saturation. This does not mean opportunity is gone. It means differentiation matters more than in a market where any store can succeed simply by opening.</p>
      <p>A new dispensary in Lewiston needs a clear reason to exist. Walking in to compete on price alone is a race to the bottom that benefits no one. Instead, consider:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Different product focus:</strong> Concentrates and extracts are underserved in Maine markets; budget flower for price-sensitive customers; edibles and beverages with consistent dosing</li>
        <li><strong>Superior customer service:</strong> Extensive budtender training, consultative sales approach, loyalty programs that actually reward loyal customers</li>
        <li><strong>Delivery service:</strong> No L-A dispensary currently offers delivery to surrounding towns—Greene, Leeds, Mechanic Falls, and other small towns have customers who would appreciate not driving to Lewiston</li>
        <li><strong>Community ties:</strong> Local brand identity, sponsorships of youth sports, participation in neighborhood events, hiring from the local community</li>
        <li><strong>Medical patient focus:</strong> A dispensary that prioritizes medical patients with higher-THC products, lower prices for cardholders, and a more clinical environment might capture a different customer segment</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Local Rules and Licensing</h2>
      <p>Lewiston requires both a Maine OCP Adult-Use Retail License and local approval through the City of Lewiston Planning and Code Department. The local approval process involves a site plan review, a public notice period, and typically a presentation before the Planning Board. This process adds 60-90 days to your timeline compared to municipalities with automatic approval upon state licensing.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>State License:</strong> OCP Adult-Use Retail License from Maine's Office of Cannabis Policy</li>
        <li><strong>Local Approval:</strong> Site plan review and conditional use approval from the Lewiston Planning Board</li>
        <li><strong>Local Annual Fee:</strong> $3,000 paid annually to the City of Lewiston</li>
        <li><strong>School Buffer:</strong> 500-foot minimum from any school property line</li>
        <li><strong>Zoning:</strong> Commercial and Planned Commercial zones only</li>
        <li><strong>Security:</strong> Must meet Maine OCP requirements including 24-hour surveillance and access-controlled storage</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Lewiston's Planning Board meets on the first and third Tuesdays of each month. Applications must be submitted at least three weeks before a meeting to be placed on the agenda. The city's planning staff is generally helpful but can be slow during peak permit seasons.</p>
    </section>

