    <section>
      <h2>Real Estate Considerations</h2>
      <p>Lewiston has several distinct commercial zones suited for dispensary development. Each has different characteristics in terms of foot traffic, parking, rent, and customer demographics.</p>
      <p>Center Street runs through the heart of downtown Lewiston, connecting the Lewiston State Office Building on the east end to the Lewiston Public Library and downtown shopping district on the west. It has the highest foot traffic from local residents and also draws customers from surrounding towns who come to Lewiston for government services and shopping. Center Street rents are premium—expect to pay $16-20 per square foot annually for ground floor retail space in good condition.</p>
      <p>Lisbon Street is the main commercial artery that runs east-west through the most densely populated sections of Lewiston. It passes through the Tree Streets neighborhood, which is one of the most walkable areas of the city. Lisbon Street draws steady traffic from local residents who live nearby and prefer not to drive downtown. Rents are moderate, typically $14-18 per square foot annually.</p>
      <p>Route 196 is the suburban commercial strip that runs along the northern edge of the city toward Brunswick. It is accessible from I-95 and offers abundant free parking. This area draws customers from the suburban neighborhoods and passing travelers. Rents are notably lower here, $12-16 per square foot, and parking is far easier than the downtown corridors.</p>
      <p>Square footage for a typical dispensary ranges from 1,200-1,800 square feet, including retail floor, back-of-house storage, security vault, and office space. A 1,500 square foot space on Lisbon Street would cost approximately $21,000-27,000 annually in rent. The 500-foot school buffer affects parcels near Lewiston High School on Central Avenue, the Lewiston Middle School on Cedar Street, and several elementary schools throughout the city. Your zoning attorney should verify compliance before signing a lease.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The Competition Reality</h2>
      <p>Lewiston-Auburn has 5-7 existing dispensaries. Before entering this market, understand what you are walking into. Each existing dispensary has accumulated regulars over years of operation—customers who have relationships with budtenders, know the product selection, and have established buying patterns. These relationships are not easily broken.</p>
      <p>The financial dynamics of entering a saturated market are unfavorable in some respects. Established stores have already absorbed their startup costs—their buildouts are depreciated, their initial inventory investments recovered, their early marketing spend behind them. A new entrant faces all those costs simultaneously. Competing purely on price means selling products below the cost basis of established competitors who can hold the line longer.</p>
      <p>Price competition is one option. It works but is risky in a market with established players. You are competing against stores that are paying off their buildouts with cash flow rather than new investment. A new store competing on price starts at a financial disadvantage that compounds over time.</p>
      <p>Differentiation is the better path. Focus on product selection—concentrates, edibles, or budget flower are underserved segments. Focus on customer experience—consultative sales rather than transactional retail. Focus on a specific niche—a clear identity makes it easier for customers to understand why they should choose you over a familiar alternative.</p>
      <p>Delivery is an underserved capability in this market. No L-A dispensary currently offers delivery to surrounding towns. Greene, Leeds, Mechanic Falls, Minot, and other small towns within 15-20 minutes of Lewiston have residents who would appreciate not driving into the city. A delivery-first or delivery-emphasis strategy could capture this underserved geography.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>What Operators Say</h2>
      <p>Lewiston operators who have succeeded emphasize community roots. This is a Franco-American city where family reputation and community ties matter. Operators who show up for local events, sponsor youth sports teams, and engage with neighborhood organizations build loyalty that no advertising budget can match.</p>
      <p>Word-of-mouth is your most powerful marketing tool in Lewiston. One enthusiastic regular can bring you five new customers. One dissatisfied regular can drive away ten. The Franco-American community is close-knit; people talk. Invest heavily in making your team excel at customer service. In Lewiston, how you treat people is the business strategy.</p>
      <p>Operators also report that the L-A market rewards consistency. Customers here value reliability above novelty. They want to walk into the same store, see the same budtenders, find the same products in stock, and have the same positive experience every time. Building that reliability takes time but creates a moat that is hard for new entrants to cross.</p>
      <p>The working-class demographic of Lewiston also affects purchasing patterns. Price sensitivity is real here. Customers compare prices and will drive across town to save a few dollars on an eighth. But working-class customers also reward quality—when they spend money, they want it to be worth it. The sweet spot in Lewiston is good quality at fair prices, not premium products at premium prices.</p>
    </section>

